commits.message:
Make behavior of `removeDirectoryRecursive` more consistent

The way `removeDirectoryRecursive dir` works right now is totally
inconsistent:

  - If there's a directory-like symbolic link, the function removes it
    without recursing into it, *unless* the symbolic link is not
    removable for some reason (e.g. no permission), in which case it
    recurses into it and wipes out everything inside.

  - If `dir` itself is actually a directory-like symbolic link, it will
    recurse into it but fail to remove `dir` itself.

The causes of these two problems are:

  - Instead of explicitly checking whether path refers to a true
    directory, it assumes any unremovable file that also satisfies
    `directoryExists` must necessarily be a directory.  This is false,
    because `directoryExists` dereferences the symbolic link.

  - `getDirectoryContents` should not be called until `dir` is verified
    to be a true directory.

There are two possible ways to handle the case where `dir` is not a true
directory:

  - One can delete it silently, similar to the behavior of the POSIX
    command `rm -r`.

  - Or one can raise an error, similar to the behavior of the Python
    function `shutil.rmtree`.

The former is more elegant to implement but for backward compatibility
`removeDirectoryRecursive` shall retain the Python-like behavior.
Another function `removePathRecursive` was added to implement the POSIX
behavior, although the decision of to export this function will be left
for the future.

On Windows, there are two kinds of symbolic links:

  - directory symbolic links, and
  - file symbolic links.

Directory symbolic links are treated as directories on Windows, which
means `lstat` considers them directories and `DeleteFile` doesn't work.
To remedy this, `removePathRecursive` was tweaked to handle these
unusual cases and avoid following symbolic links.

issue.title: Sortable Enabled / Frozen Dynamically? (v3)
issue.body:
Hello,

I was wondering how we can disable sorting dynamically without killing the table and recreating it. Or, just a way to "freeze" sorting at the current state / order? Or dynamically get it back to the default order, again without killing the table and recreating it.

And is there an easy way to know if someone has changed the order at all? As in, can I programmability find out it the default / initialized sort is the current sort order? Within filter I can see what filters are being used (if any) by reviewing:

```
var filtering = FooTable.get('#table_name').use(FooTable.Filtering);
// Do something with filtering.filters
```
But I can not seem to find something like this for sorting.

Also, the documentation seems to be off a little under the Enabled section:

http://fooplugins.github.io/FooTable/docs/components/sorting.html

It mentions:

issue.body: **Problems** Getting DevOps to run management commands takes quite a bit of time to escalate the critical issues quickly. We often wait for DevOps to execute the commands and then observe the results, so a lot of important time is lost. **Solution** Have a maintenance dashboard for the escalation team that let them interact with advance views for executing the management commands ( which would be replaced by the views eventually). More on Maintenance App [here](https://openedx.atlassian.net/wiki/display/SUST/Maintenance+Board) Here is the basic layout of the `Maintenance App`. Home page adds the the shortcut to maintenace app via a user-account-dropdown `studio_url/maintenance` url shows the list of the views available `studio_url/maintenance/force_publish_course` url : shows force publish course view And the rest of the pages would follow the same pattern, Here is the list of all the commands that we may want. `studio_url/maintenance/show_orphans` `studio_url/maintenance/delete_orphans` `studio_url/maintenance/export_course` `studio_url/maintenance/import_course` `studio_url/maintenance/delete_course` the`/maintenance` would look like this when these views are implemented. issue.title: Fast Calculation of Area Under ROC curve
issue.body:
The area under the ROC curve can be calculated directly from a vector of predictions and a vector of binary labels using the [Mann-Whitney U Test](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#Area-under-curve_.28AUC.29_statistic_for_ROC_curves). Since this algorithm does not require calculating the ROC curve, it can provide a significant performance increase. My benchmarks on show that, on 10 million observations, this algorithm is six times faster than calculating AUROC with your package (18.3 seconds vs 2.9 seconds).

Would you be interested in adding a C++ implementation of this algorithm to your package? The speedup that this algorithm provides would be valuable for users who need to evaluate hundreds to thousands of models (e.g. with a grid search over a feature / hyper-parameter space).

If you are interested in outside contributions to your package, please let me know.

comment.body:
Thank you for an interesting suggestion and the link. I used the U statistic calculation of `wilcox.test` and compared with precrec on Linux and OS X. Precrec was faster in my test cases, but I could see it would perform much better with more efficient implementation. 

Precrec has an own C++ version of `rank` function internally, and by using it, I suppose the implementation of an efficient U statistic calculation shouldn't be too difficult. I may try to include this in precrec.

It would be great if you could contribute to the package. Unfortunately, I haven't prepared any proper documentations or policies for it, yet.

Below are the results of my test cases.

```R
# Test code
library(precrec)

# A sample of 10,000,000
samp1 <- create_sim_samples(1, 5000000, 5000000)
scores1 <- samp1$scores[[1]][[1]]
samp1.x <- scores1[1:5000000]
samp1.y <- scores1[5000001:10000000]

# Precrec
func_precrec <- function(samp) {
   curves <- evalmod(scores = samp$scores, labels = samp$labels)
   aucs <- auc(curves)
}

# U statistic
func_u <- function(x, y) {
   n.x <- as.numeric(length(x))
   n.y <- as.numeric(length(y))
   r <- rank(c(x, y))
   U <- sum(r[seq_along(x)]) - n.x * (n.x + 1) / 2
   uauc <- U / (n.x * n.y)
}
```

Linux - i7, 3.4GHz, 16 GB
```R
> # Process time
> system.time(res1 <- func_precrec(samp1))
   user  system elapsed 
  4.350   0.249   4.600 
> system.time(res2 <- func_u(samp1.x, samp1.y))
   user  system elapsed 
  7.943   0.059   8.004 
> 
> # AUCs
> res1
  modnames dsids curvetypes      aucs
1       m1     1        ROC 0.5001329
2       m1     1        PRC 0.5001741
> res2
[1] 0.5001329
```

issue.title: Memory Allocation on Saddle Points Exercise
issue.body:
I just solved Saddle Points exercise on C track and could not resolve it without a memory leak, using valgrind to check. I have checked all solutions published and all have the same memory leak issue.

The structs of this solution are:
```
typedef struct {                                                                
   size_t row, column;                                                          
} saddle_point_t;                                                               
                                                                                
typedef struct {                                                                
   size_t count;                                                                
   saddle_point_t points[];                                                     
} saddle_points_t; 
```

In file [test_saddle_points.c](https://github.com/exercism/c/blob/master/exercises/saddle-points/test/test_saddle_points.c), `free()` is called just for the main struct `saddle_points_t`, but not for the field `points`.

The [example.c](https://github.com/exercism/c/blob/master/exercises/saddle-points/src/example.c) uses `realloc()` and calculates the size of the main struct + points field, so the `free()` works fine and there is no memory leak.
```
realloc(saddle_points,                                                                                                                                                    
            sizeof(saddle_points_t) +       
            sizeof(saddle_point_t) *        
            ++count);
```

However, I think this approach is not very common, and we can see that all students have submit solutions using `calloc()` for the main struct and another `calloc()` for points field. It's part of mentoring program to check if the solution handles memory allocation correctly and we provide a valgrind option on `make`.

I was expecting the test to free fields point too:
```
free(actual->points)
```

Another minor issue is that students should implement function `saddlePoints`, but the naming convention we have been using for C track is snake_case, so it should be `saddle_points`.

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: New feature or request

issue.body:
Make a formal request to the Cloud CoE to have our own Cloud Sandbox instance in order to get our own "play with docker" environment.

_Specific usages_
- Public Cloud space to preview Presentations

_Reasoning_
- Play-with-docker does not have the reliability needed (it is sometimes out of capacity and cannot create sessions)
- Work laptops do not allow virtualisation to install docker
- Personal laptops require to have Windows Professional to create virtualisation (or linux). Otherwise one would need to install some tricky software to simulate virtualization (is that even a thing??)
- Even if personal laptops were an option, it limits our ability to be productive should certain families share laptops between spouses and kids (cough cough)

first: "*substantial periods (months to years) of limited or no exposure following L2 training*"
second: "*months to years*"

Does GUM format allow non-continuous span of mentions (e.g. `MentionSpan=4-5,11-18`, i.e. "*substantial periods of limited or no exposure following L2 training*")?

Early testing caught this segfault on non-Windows platforms (see #2059 and libxml@956534e) but it was incompletely fixed and is still an issue on Windows platforms that are using system DLLs.

We work around this by configuring libxml2 in this situation to use its default memory management functions. - ~~login on the openstack qcow2 image is broken, the default credentials do not work~~ (fixed by @schaefi, the image had its root console deactivated)

pull_request.title: Implement project configurator
pull_request.body:
Initial pass to fix https://github.com/gitpod-io/gitpod/issues/4648

Depends on & contains https://github.com/gitpod-io/gitpod/pull/4846

What it does:

- Adds a `config` (text) field to `d_b_project`, so that Projects can have a custom `.gitpod.yml` content
- Adds a Project Configurator view in the dashboard, as final step in the Add Project flow (also currently accessible via a Project's UI)
- When determining the config of a new workspace, use this priority order:
    1. From repository
    2. (_new_) From Project DB
    3. From definitely-gp
    4. Derived (Go) or default
- When starting from a custom `.gitpod.yml` (from the Project DB), the initializer also places the uncomitted `.gitpod.yml` into the workspace (to encourage repo-based configs)

How to test:

- Create a new team
- Add a new project (either by inserting into `d_b_project`, or we set up a GitHub App integration -- @AlexTugarev could you help with the latter?)
- If the project already has a repo-based config, the configurator should indicate that and be disabled. If there is no repo config, the configurator should allow you to write a new `.gitpod.yml` (e.g. based on one of the presets) and then test it / iterate on it in a quick loop (with the build output on the right)

The UX of this is still rough, but the goal is to add this final step rather soon, and then iterate on the entire Add Project flow.
